items.content_html:
I need some help with this one ! @ddbeck

The Web Speech API spec recently changed the event property SpeechSynthesisEvent.elapsedTime from milliseconds to seconds:

  • FF95 has made this change in https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1732498
  • Chromium issue (not fixed) is https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1253036
  • Safari 14.1.2 on macOS appears to do the right thing (seconds) according to this https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1732498#c0 . I have no information on when it changed.

There is a demo fiddle here https://jsfiddle.net/ybe1c6ot/ (comes from this issue).

What's the best way to update SpeechSynthesisEvent.elapsedTime?
We could use the following options

  1. a single note about the changes in the current version, or
  2. a new version with notes, or
  3. a subfeature to indicate when the version changed.

I have tried the first two of these approaches so you can get a feel for the difference. I lean towards the second option though the first is much easier to roll out and likely more consistent.

How do we mark up the event handlers and events that fire an event of this type?
E.g. SpeechSynthesisUtterance.onend) fires SpeechSynthesisUtterance end_event.

I was thinking we might use option 1 for both of these.
Technically the event handler should not need to be marked up. But IMO this is likely to get us into trouble because this is where people may well find the incompatibility. What do you think?

P.S.

  • Related issue that this will fix: #12595
  • Docs tracking: mdn/content#10221
items.title: SpeechSynthesisEvent.elapsedTime spec change ms to s

items.content_html:
This changes the Digest and Want-Digest HTTP header support from true to null for all platforms.

  • true is incorrect because the browser does nothing with these headers.
  • false is correct because there are things a browser could do with these headers. However if we used false the table would be empty, and we normally don't allow all-false data.
  • null is a compromise, which essentially says "we don't know" (but at least we're not pretending it is supported in some way). It will force us to return to this question in the near future when we start enforcing better data quality on the HTTP section. At that time I am hoping we allow false and a note to be added as top level support option for all browsers so this can be explained.

There is a discussion on this in #12533 and mdn/content#9139. The decision for now was that we set this as null and perhaps revisit later.
items.title: Mark HTTP digest and want-digest support as null/unknown

items.content_html: This PR removes the MessageEventSource_type subfeature of the MessageEvent API's source member. This is a WebIDL typedef that defines a WindowProxy (formerly just Window), MessagePort, or ServiceWorker. To the end web developer, this typedef is indistinguishable, thus there is no need to include this as a BCD feature.
items.title: Remove api.MessageEvent.source.MessageEventSource_type

items.content_html:
Error constructor specifies that the constructor takes arguments message, options.cause, fileName, lineNumber.

fileName, lineNumber are in javascript/builtins/Error.json as properties, but not listed as error constructor options - so they aren't visible in MDN on the error constructor page.

This reproduces the data for the properties under the error constructor. Note that it does NOT reproduce message, which is assumed to match the parent constructor function.

This is part of fixing #10159
items.title: Error constructor missing filename/linenumber parameters
